    The program crashes with a heap buffer overflow, and the stack trace        
    points to print_reverse at line 11, specifically within the for loop        
    starting at line 10:                                                        
                                                                                
                                                                                
     for (size_t i = v.size() - 1; i >= 0; i--) {                               
         std::printf("%d\n", v[i]);                                             
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Step-by-step Analysis                                                       
                                                                                
    1. Variable Type Mismatch: size_t vs. Signed Loop Counter                   
                                                                                
    The loop variable i is declared as size_t, which is an unsigned type        
    (typically unsigned long or unsigned int on macOS/Linux).                   
                                                                                
    The loop condition is:                                                      
                                                                                
                                                                                
     i >= 0                                                                     
                                                                                
                                                                                
    However, size_t is unsigned. In unsigned arithmetic:                        
                                                                                
     • The smallest value size_t can hold is 0.                                 
     • When i is 0 and we decrement (i--), it wraps around to the maximum       
       value of size_t (e.g., 18446744073709551615 on 64-bit systems).          
                                                                                
    Thus, after i becomes 0, the next iteration does:                           
                                                                                
                                                                                
     i-- -> becomes a very large positive number (wraparound)                   
                                                                                
                                                                                
    And since i >= 0 is always true for unsigned values, the loop runs          
    forever.                                                                    
                                                                                
    Eventually, the code accesses v[i] with this huge index:                    
                                                                                
                                                                                
     std::printf("%d\n", v[i]);                                                 
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Since i is now effectively a massive number (e.g., 2^64 - 1), this          
    accesses memory far beyond the bounds of the vector v, causing a heap       
    buffer overflow.                                                            
                                                                                
    2. Why the Error Occurs on empty Vector                                     
                                                                                
    The main function calls print_reverse twice:                                
                                                                                
                                                                                
     print_reverse(v);     // v has 3 elements                                  
     print_reverse(empty); // empty has 0 elements                              
                                                                                
                                                                                
     • On the first call (v), the loop runs correctly: i = 2, 1, 0, then i--    
       becomes 0 → i-- → 0xFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFF, then i >= 0 is true, so infinite   
       loop → crash.                                                            
     • The same issue happens on the empty vector, but it crashes even faster   
       because v.size() == 0, so i = 0 - 1, which is size_t(-1), again the max  
       value → loop runs infinitely → heap overflow.                            
                                                                                
    3. Why frame variable i and v Fail to Show?                                 
                                                                                
    Despite the stack trace pointing into the print_reverse function, debug     
    fails to show i or v. This suggests:                                        
                                                                                
     • The debug info may be incomplete or optimized out.                       
     • The program may have already crashed before i could be reconstructed in  
       the debugger.                                                            
     • However, this does not contradict our analysis — the crash occurs        
       during execution of the loop body, and the debugger isn't able to        
       capture debug state at the time of the crash due to buffer overflow      
       corrupting the stack.                                                    
                                                                                
    4. Why This Is a Classic Signed/Unsigned Pitfall                            
                                                                                
    The core bug is using an unsigned type (size_t) for a loop index that must  
    decrement to zero and then go below zero. The expectation in a reverse      
    loop is that i >= 0 should stop at zero, but for size_t, i >= 0 is always   
    true.                                                                       
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Root Cause                                                                  
                                                                                
    ▌ The loop uses size_t as the index, which is unsigned. When i reaches 0    
    ▌ and is decremented, it wraps to the maximum value of size_t, making       
    ▌ the condition i >= 0 always true, resulting in infinite loop and heap     
    ▌ buffer overflow on v[i] with invalid index.                               
                                                                                
    This is a signed/unsigned integer comparison bug, common in C++ when using  
    std::vector::size() (returns size_t) in a loop with decrements.             
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Fix                                                                         
                                                                                
    ✅ Minimal Local Fix (Quick correction):                                    
                                                                                
    Use a signed integer type for the loop index:                               
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static void print_reverse(const std::vector<int>& v) {                     
         for (int i = static_cast<int>(v.size()) - 1; i >= 0; i--) {            
             std::printf("%d\n", v[i]);                                         
         }                                                                      
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    ▌ This fixes the immediate bug: int can go negative, so i >= 0 fails        
    ▌ correctly when i becomes -1.                                              
                                                                                
    ▌ But note: static_cast<int>(v.size()) risks overflow if the vector has     
    ▌ more than INT_MAX elements. In practice, this is unlikely.                
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    ✅ Thorough Root-Cause Fix (Safer and More Robust):                         
                                                                                
    Use a reverse iterator instead of manual indexing — the idiomatic, safe     
    C++ way:                                                                    
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static void print_reverse(const std::vector<int>& v) {                     
         for (auto it = v.rbegin(); it != v.rend(); ++it) {                     
             std::printf("%d\n", *it);                                          
         }                                                                      
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    ▌ This avoids integer arithmetic entirely. It is safe, readable, and        
    ▌ idiomatic. No risk of overflow or incorrect loop bounds.                  
                                                                                
    Alternatively, if you want to keep the numbered loop (e.g., for learning),  
    use a safe signed type and handle large vectors:                            
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static void print_reverse(const std::vector<int>& v) {                     
         int size = static_cast<int>(v.size());                                 
         for (int i = size - 1; i >= 0; i--) {                                  
             std::printf("%d\n", v[i]);                                         
         }                                                                      
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    ▌ Still safer than size_t, as long as vector size is less than INT_MAX.     
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Why the find_definition for size_t Was Useful                               
                                                                                
    We checked the definition of size_t:                                        
                                                                                
                                                                                
     typedef __darwin_size_t size_t;                                            
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Note that __darwin_size_t is an unsigned type (e.g., unsigned long on       
    macOS). This confirms that size_t is always unsigned, so any loop using it  
    for i >= 0 comparisons with decrement risks infinite iteration.             
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
     1 Immediate Fix: Replace size_t i with int i in the loop and cast          
       v.size() to int. This is sufficient for most use cases.                  
     2 Best Practice Fix: Use auto it = v.rbegin(); it != v.rend(); ++it to     
       avoid manual index manipulation entirely.                                
     3 Prevention: Enable compiler warnings (-Wsign-compare, -Wconversion,      
       -Wall) to catch such issues during compilation.                          
                                                                                
    The root cause is definitively the unsigned size_t in a decrementing loop   
    with i >= 0 condition, leading to infinite loop and buffer overflow.        
                                                                                
